# Zero-Cost DSAEngine: Local MCP Stdio Server for Coding Agents
> Supports 7 AI coding agents — Claude Code, Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Windsurf, Kiro, Augment Code, Google Antigravity

## The Core Insight

You **don't need to pay for AI APIs**. Here's why:

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  USER types prompt in Cursor/Windsurf/Antigravity            │
│  ↓                                                           │
│  Agent's LLM (already paid via subscription) reads           │
│  .cursorrules → sees "always consult DSAEngine first"        │
│  ↓                                                           │
│  LLM calls dsa_classify("friend suggestions in social app") │
│  ↓                                                           │
│  DSAEngine (local Rust binary, stdin/stdout) responds:       │
│  "Use BFS for mutual friends O(V+E), Union-Find O(α(n))"   │
│  ↓                                                           │
│  LLM writes optimized code using DSAEngine's guidance       │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**The agent's own LLM is your free AI classifier.** Your DSAEngine just needs to be a fast, local, deterministic tool server.

## How "Runs Before Every Prompt" Works

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This is achieved through **two layers**, both zero-cost:

### Layer 1: Rules Files (Prompt Injection)

Files like `.cursorrules`, `.windsurfrules`, `CLAUDE.md` are **prepended to every single user prompt** by the coding agent. We write a rules file that says:

```
You have access to DSAEngine MCP tools. BEFORE writing ANY code that involves
arrays, graphs, trees, caching, sorting, searching, or string processing,
you MUST call `dsa_classify` first to get the optimal algorithm.
NEVER implement brute-force when DSAEngine has a better solution.
```

This makes the LLM (which the user already pays for) act as the intelligent router on every prompt.

### Layer 2: MCP Stdio Protocol

The Rust binary runs as a local child process. The coding agent spawns it, communicates over stdin/stdout using JSON-RPC 2.0. **No HTTP, no hosting, no API keys, no network.**

